[[File:Gerard Casey Black & White Portrait.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Gerard Casey]] '''Gerard N. Casey''' (born 1951) is an Irish academic who was Professor Emeritus at [[University College Dublin]].
==Career== He holds law degrees from the [[University of London]] and UCD as well as a primary degree in philosophy from [[University College Cork]], an MA and PhD from the [[University of Notre Dame]] and the higher doctorate, DLitt, from the National University of Ireland. He was formerly Assistant Professor at The Catholic University of America (Washington, D.C.), 1983-1986 and Adjunct Professor at the Pontifical Institute in Washington D.C., 1984-86.<ref>[http://www.ucd.ie/research/people/philosophy/professorgerardcasey/ Gerard Casey's UCD home page]</ref> He was a member of the School of Philosophy in [[University College Dublin]] (UCD) (Head from 2001–2006) from 1986 until he retired in December 2015. He is a Fellow of Mises UK and an Associated Scholar of the [[Ludwig von Mises Institute]] in [[Auburn, Alabama]].<ref>[https://www.mises.org/profile/gerard-n-casey Gerard Casey's Ludwig von Mises profile page]</ref>
==Activism and authorship== [[File:Gerard_Casey_and_Fay_Weldon_appearing_on_After_Dark_in_1997.jpg|thumb|left|Appearing with [[Fay Weldon]] on British television discussion programme ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]'' in 1997]] He was active in Irish politics in the 1990s and led the [[Christian Solidarity Party]] between 1993 and 1999. He now holds libertarian and (philosophically) anarchistic views.<ref>"Meddling in other men's affairs: the Case for Anarchy," ''Economic Affairs'' 27 (2007)4: pp. 46–51. [http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/118494730/abstract?CRETRY=1&SRETRY=0]</ref><ref>“Where Does Law Come From?” ''Philosophical Inquiry'', 32 (2010)3-4: pp. 85–92.</ref><ref>“Legal Polycentrism,” ''[[Journal of Libertarian Studies]]'', 22 (2010)1: pp. 22–34.</ref><ref>“Constitutions of No Authority: Spoonerian Reflections,” ''Independent Review'', 14 (2010)3: pp. 325–340.</ref> His philosophical interests include political philosophy (Libertarianism, [[Anarcho-capitalism]]) and the philosophy of law. He appears from time to time on radio and TV on topical social and political issues.
''Murray Rothbard'' (Vol. 15 in the series ''Major Conservative and Libertarian Thinkers'') was published by Continuum in 2010<ref>Casey, Gerard (2010). John Meadowcroft, ed. ''Murray Rothbard: Major Conservative and Libertarian Thinkers''. '''15'''. London: The Continuum International Publishing Group, Inc.</ref> and became available in paperback in August 2013. ''Libertarian Anarchy: Against the State'', was published by Continuum in July 2012 (UK) [September 2012 USA]. A comprehensive history of political thought from the perspective of liberty, ''Freedom's Progress?'', was published by Imprint Academic in September 2017.<ref>http://books.imprint.co.uk/book/?gcoi=71157100399860</ref><ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1845409426</ref><ref>https://www.bookdepository.com/Freedoms-Progress-Gerard-Casey/9781845409425?ref=bd_recs_1_1</ref>
== Books == * ''Born Alive: The Legal Status of the Unborn Child'' (Barry Rose, 2005) {{ISBN|1 902681 46 0}} * ''Murray Rothbard'' (Continuum, 2010) Vol. 15 in the series ''Major Conservative and Libertarian Thinkers'' {{ISBN|978-1441100795}} * ''Libertarian Anarchy: Against the State'' (Continuum, 2012) {{ISBN| 978-1441144676}} * ''Freedom's Progress?: A History of Political Thought'' (Imprint Academic, 2017) {{ISBN|978-1845409425}}
