{{Infobox person | name = Urso of Calabria | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 1225 | death_place = | nationality = [[Italy|Italian]] | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Philosopher }}
'''Urso of Calabria''' also Urso of Salerno, Ursus Salernitanus, Urso di Calabria. (died 1225) was an [[Italy|Italian]] scholastic philosopher and significant author of medical works in the [[school of Salerno]]. He has been thought the leading figure of the school<ref>Brian Lawns, ''The Salernitan Questions. An Introduction to the History of Medieval and Renaissance Problem Literature'' (1963), Introduction.</ref> and its most important theoretician and Aristotelian.<ref>[http://www.myriobiblos.gr/texts/english/Walter_Berschin_33.html Walter Berschin - 3. Amalfi, Salerno, Benevento, Monte Cassino<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He had a [[Europe]]an reputation.<ref>Donald Matthew, ''The Norman Kingdom of Sicily'' (1992), p. 117.</ref>
==Works== *Anatomia *Compendium de urinis *De commixtionibus elementorum *Glossulae *De effectibus medicinarum *De effectibus qualitatum *De criticis diebus *De pulsibus *De saporibus et numero eorundem *Aphorismi<ref>[http://www.mgh.de/~Poetae/Autorenliste/AutorenU.htm]; see also [http://www-cgi.uni-regensburg.de/Fakultaeten/Philosophie/Infotek/phil/view/Google/repu.html] under Urso Salernitanus.</ref>
