'''William Lane Craig''' (born August 23, 1949) is an American [[analytic philosophy|analytic philosopher]] and [[Christian theologian]].{{sfn|Creel|2014|p=205}} He holds faculty positions at [[Talbot School of Theology]] ([[Biola University]]) and [[Houston Baptist University]]. Craig has developed and defended the [[Kalam cosmological argument]] for the [[existence of God]]. He also focused in his published work on a historical argument for the [[resurrection of Jesus]]. His research on [[divine aseity]] and [[Platonism]] culminated with his book ''God Over All''. He has also debated the existence of God with public figures such as [[Sam Harris]], [[Christopher Hitchens]], [[Lawrence M. Krauss]] <ref name="Schneider 2013">{{cite news |last=Schneider |first=Nathan |author-link=Nathan Schneider |date=July 1, 2013 |title=The New Theist: How William Lane Craig Cecame Christian Philosophy's Boldest Apostle |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/The-New-Theist/140019 |website=The Chronicle of Higher Education |location=Washington |access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> and [[A. C. Grayling]] <ref>https://www.premierchristianradio.com/Shows/Saturday/Unbelievable/Episodes/Unbelievable-5-Jul-2011-William-Lane-Craig-vs-AC-Grayling-debate-on-God-Evil</ref> Craig established and runs the online apologetics ministry ReasonableFaith.org.

==Life and career==
Born August 23, 1949, in [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]], [[Illinois]], Craig is {{citation needed span |date=September 2018 |text=the second of three children}} born to Mallory and Doris Craig.{{sfn|"William Lane Craig"|2007}}<ref name="rf-cv">{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Curriculum Vitae |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/william-lane-craig/curriculum-vitae |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601130720/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/william-lane-craig/curriculum-vitae |archive-date=June 1, 2017 |access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref> His father's work with the T.&nbsp;P.&nbsp;&&nbsp;W. [[railroad]] took the family to [[Keokuk, Iowa|Keokuk]], [[Iowa]], until his transfer to the home office in [[East Peoria]] in 1960. While a student at [[East Peoria Community High School]] (1963–1967),<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Debating |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/debating |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512214855/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/debating |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 8, 2014}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}} Craig became a championship debater and public speaker,{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=211}} being named his senior year to the all-state debate team and winning the state championship in oratory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Records and History&nbsp;– Original Oratory |url=http://www.ihsa.org/SportsActivities/IndividualEvents/RecordsHistory.aspx?url=/data/ie/records/index.htm |publisher=Illinois High School Association |access-date=May 27, 2015}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=January 2018}} In September 1965, his junior year, he converted to Christianity,<ref name="Faculty Profile">{{cite web |title=William Lane Craig |url=http://www.talbot.edu/faculty/profile/william_craig/ |location=La Mirada, California |publisher=Biola University |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814023848/http://www.talbot.edu/faculty/profile/william_craig/ |archive-date=August 14, 2014 |access-date=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=William Lane Craig and Sean McDowell |url=http://fervr.net/author/37132/ |website=Fervr |access-date=May 11, 2014}}</ref> and after graduating from high school,{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} attended [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]], majoring in communications.{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=212}} Craig graduated in 1971{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=211}} and the following year married his wife Jan,{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} whom he met on the staff of [[Campus Crusade for Christ]].{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=211}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Schneider |first=Nathan |author-link=Nathan Schneider |date=July 12, 2013 |title=7 Habits of a Highly Effective Philosopher |url=http://killingthebuddha.com/mag/witness/7-habits-of-a-highly-effective-philosopher/ |website=Killing the Buddha |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, he was named alumnus of the year by Wheaton.<ref name="Wheaton College">{{cite web |date=May 7, 2014 |title=Dr. William Lane Craig Named Alumnus of the Year |url=http://www.wheaton.edu/Media-Center/News/2014/05/Dr-William-Lane-Craig-Named-Alumnus-of-the-Year |location=Wheaton, Illinois |publisher=Wheaton College |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512213253/https://www.wheaton.edu/Media-Center/News/2014/05/Dr-William-Lane-Craig-Named-Alumnus-of-the-Year |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 11, 2014}}</ref>

In 1973 Craig entered the program in [[philosophy of religion]] at [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]] north of [[Chicago]], where he studied under [[Norman Geisler]].{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|pp=211–212}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Double Doctorates |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/double-doctorates |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231322/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/double-doctorates |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> In 1975 Craig commenced doctoral studies in philosophy at the [[University of Birmingham]] in [[England]], writing on the cosmological argument{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} under the direction of [[John Hick]].{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=211}} He was awarded a doctorate in 1977.{{sfnm |1a1=Robinson |1a2=Baggett |1y=2016 |1p=211 |2a1="William Lane Craig" |2y=2007}} Out of this study came his first book, ''The Kalam Cosmological Argument'' (1979), a defense of the argument he first encountered in Hackett's work.  Craig was awarded a [[postdoctoral fellowship]] in 1978 from the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]] to pursue research on the historicity of the [[resurrection of Jesus]] under the direction of [[Wolfhart Pannenberg]] at the [[University of Munich|Ludwig-Maximillians-Universität München]] in [[Germany]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} His studies in [[Munich]] under Pannenberg's supervision led to a second doctorate, this one in theology,<ref name="Wheaton College"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=April 28, 2013 |title=Creation and Evolution (Part 2) |url=https://www.reasonablefaith.org/podcasts/defenders-podcast-series-2/s2-creation-and-evolution/creation-and-evolution-part-2/ |website=Defenders Podcast |publisher=Reasonable Faith |access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> awarded in 1984 with the publication of his doctoral thesis, ''The Historical Argument for the Resurrection of Jesus During the [[Deist]] Controversy'' (1985).{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

Craig joined the faculty of [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]] in 1980, where he taught philosophy of religion for the next seven years. In 1982 Craig received an invitation to debate [[Kai Nielsen (philosopher)|Kai Nielsen]] at the [[University of Calgary]], Canada, on the question of [[God's existence]],{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} and has since then debated many philosophers, scientists, and biblical scholars.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Stafforini |first=Pablo |date=August 18, 2016 |title=William Lane Craig: A Complete List of Debates |url=http://www.stafforini.com/blog/william-lane-craig-a-complete-list-of-debates/ |dead-url=no |website=Pablo's Miscellany |publisher=Pablo Stafforini |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611042017/http://www.stafforini.com/blog/william-lane-craig-a-complete-list-of-debates/ |archive-date=June 11, 2017 |access-date=October 16, 2016}}</ref>

After a one-year stint at [[Westmont College]]<ref name="rf-cv"/> on the outskirts of [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], Craig moved in 1987 with his wife and two young children back to Europe,{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} where he pursued research for the next seven years as a visiting scholar at the [[KU Leuven|Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]] ([[Louvain, Belgium|Louvain]]) in Belgium.{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=212}} Out of that period of research issued seven books, among them ''God, Time, and Eternity'' (2001).{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} In 1994, Craig joined the Department of Philosophy and Ethics at [[Talbot School of Theology]] in suburban [[Los Angeles]] as a [[Research Professor]] of Philosophy, a position he currently{{as of when|date=September 2018}} holds,<ref name="Faculty Profile"/> and he went on to become a Professor of Philosophy at [[Houston Baptist University]] in 2014. In 2016, Craig was named Alumnus of the Year by [[Trinity Evangelical Divinity School]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Trinity International University |author-link=Trinity International University |date=July 22, 2016 |title=William Lane Craig Named TEDS Alumnus of the Year |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/buffalo-grove/community/chi-ugc-article-william-lane-craig-named-teds-alumnus-of-the-2016-07-22-story.html |work=Buffalo Grove Countryside |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726205730/http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/buffalo-grove/community/chi-ugc-article-william-lane-craig-named-teds-alumnus-of-the-2016-07-22-story.html |archive-date=July 26, 2016 |access-date=September 30, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Biola created a permanent faculty position and endowed chair, the William Lane Craig Endowed Chair in Philosophy, in honor of Craig's academic contributions.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Wu |first=Joanna |date=Spring 2017 |title=William Lane Craig Named in Biola's First Endowed Chair |url=http://magazine.biola.edu/article/17-spring/william-lane-craig-named-in-biolas-first-endowed-c/ |magazine=Biola Magazine |location=La Mirada, California |publisher=Biola University |page=15 |access-date=September 30, 2018}}</ref>

Craig served as president of the [[Philosophy of Time Society]] from 1999 to 2006.{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=213}} He helped found the [[Evangelical Philosophical Society]] and served as its president from 1996 to 2005.{{sfn|Robinson|Baggett|2016|p=213}}

==Research==

===Kalam cosmological argument===
{{see also|Kalam cosmological argument}}
Craig has worked extensively on a version of the [[cosmological argument]] called the ''[[Kalam cosmological argument]]''.{{sfnm |1a1=Cowan |1a2=Spiegel |1y=2009 |1pp=268–269<!-- "The Kalam argument originated with Arabic philosophers in the Middle Ages but has recently been taken up by Christian philosophers, especially William Lane Craig and J.P. Moreland." --> |2a1=Jackson |2y=2014 |2p=19<!-- "One person who has studied the kalam cosmological argument extensively is the modern philosopher William L. Craig (1949–)" --> |3a1=Peterson |3a2=Hasker |3a3=Reichenbach |3a4=Basinger |3y=2013 |3pp=86–89 |4a1=Reichenbach |4y=2017<!-- "[The Kalām cosmological argument] has a venerable history, especially in the Islamic ''mutakalliman'' tradition. Although it had numerous defenders through the centuries, it received new life in the recent voluminous writings of William Lane Craig." --> |5a1=Williams |5y=2013 |5p=89<!-- "William Lane Craig has revived the kalam argument in the late 20th century, discussing it in the light of modern scientific cosmology." -->}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Who's Who: Modern Authors: William Lane Craig (Entry 2) |url=http://www.philosophyofreligion.info/whos-who/modern-authors/william-lane-craig/ |website=Philosophy of Religion.info |access-date=16 October 2016<!--|quote=Craig is best known for his extensive work on the kalam cosmological argument, and has also published material on the philosophy of time and on divine foreknowledge.-->}}</ref> While the ''Kalam'' has a venerable history in [[medieval]] [[Islamic]] philosophy, Craig updated the argument to interact with contemporary scientific and philosophical developments.{{whose quote}} Craig's research resulted in renewed contemporary interest in the argument, and in cosmological arguments in general; the philosopher [[Quentin Smith]] states: "a count of the articles in the philosophy journals shows that more articles have been published about Craig's defense of the Kalam argument than have been published about any other philosopher’s contemporary formulation of an argument for God's existence."{{sfn|Smith|2007|p=183}}

Craig formulates his ''Kalām Cosmological Argument'' in the following manner:
# Everything that begins to exist has a cause of its existence.
# The universe began to exist.
# Therefore, the universe has a cause of its existence.<ref>Craig outlines this argument and seven others for the existence of God in {{cite magazine |last=Craig |first=William Lane |year=2013 |title=Does God Exist? |url=http://philosophynow.org/issues/99/Does_God_Exist |magazine=Philosophy Now |issue=99 |location=London |issn=0961-5970 |access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref>

In his later literature, Craig sometimes uses a more modest version of the first premise, in order to bypass certain issues:
# If the universe began to exist, then the universe has a cause of its beginning.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=The ''Kalam'' Cosmological Argument |url=https://www.reasonablefaith.org/writings/popular-writings/existence-nature-of-god/the-kalam-cosmological-argument/ |website=Reasonable Faith |access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref>

Philosophically, Craig uses two traditional arguments to show that [[temporal finitism|time is finite]]: he argues that the existence of an [[actual infinite]] is [[metaphysical possibility|metaphysically impossible]], and that forming an actual infinite through successive addition is metaphysically impossible.{{sfn|Craig|Sinclair|2009|p=103}}

Granting the strict logical consistency of [[Georg Cantor|post-Cantorian]], [[axiomatic set theory|axiomatized infinite set theory]], Craig concludes that the existence of an actually infinite number of things is metaphysically impossible due to the consequential absurdities that arise.{{sfn|Craig|Sinclair|2009|pp=106–107}} Craig illustrates this point using the example of [[Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel]]. In Hilbert's hypothetical fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms, one can add an additional guest in room #1 by moving the guest in room #1 to room #2, the guest in room #2 into room #3, the guest in room #3 into room #4 and continue the shifting of rooms out to infinity. Craig points out that it is absurd to add an additional guest to a fully occupied hotel and the absurd result that the hotel has the same number of guests, infinity, both before after adding the additional guest.{{sfn|Oppy|1995}} Stating that the mathematical conventions stipulated to ensure the logical consistency of this type of [[transfinite arithmetic]] have no [[ontology|ontological]] force, Craig concludes that finitism is most plausibly true, which means that the series of past events in the universe must be finite, so it must have had a beginning.{{sfn|Reichenbach|2013}}

Craig says that just as it is impossible, despite the proponents of "[[supertask|super-tasks]]", to count to infinity, so it is metaphysically impossible to count down from infinity.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=May 17, 2009 |title=Pruss on Forming an Actual Infinite by Successive Addition |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/pruss-on-forming-an-actual-infinite-by-successive-addition |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806091418/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/pruss-on-forming-an-actual-infinite-by-successive-addition |archive-date=May 18, 2009 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Craig says that an inversion of the story of [[Tristram Shandy]] is a counter-intuitive absurdity that could result from the formation of an actual infinite. Craig claims that if the universe were eternal, an infinite number of events would have occurred before the present moment, which he says is impossible.{{sfn|Craig|1979}}

One of Craig's contributions to the kalam cosmological argument is his reference to [[astrophysics]] in support of the universe's beginning, namely the [[expansion of the universe]] and [[thermodynamics]].{{sfn|Craig|Sinclair|2009|p=125}}

Craig says that the [[Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker metric]] [[Big Bang]] model predicts a [[cosmic singularity]], which marks the origin of the universe in the finite past.{{sfn|Craig|1992}} Craig says that competing models which do not imply an origin of the universe have either proved to be untenable (such as the [[steady state model]] and [[vacuum fluctuation]] models) or implied the beginning of the universe they were designed to avoid ([[oscillating universe|oscillating models]], [[inflationary model]]s, [[quantum gravity|quantum gravity models]]). Craig says that the Borde-[[Alan Guth|Guth]]-[[Alexander Vilenkin|Vilenkin]] theorem of 2003 requires that any universe which has on average been in a state of [[cosmic expansion]] cannot be [[eternity|eternal]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Mitchell |first=Jacqueline |date=May 29, 2012 |title=In the Beginning Was the Beginning |url=http://now.tufts.edu/articles/beginning-was-beginning |website=Tufts Now |location=Medford, Massachusetts |publisher=Tufts University |access-date=May 8, 2014}}</ref>

Craig believes that recent discoveries about the expansion of the universe and [[relativity theory]] support his view that thermodynamic properties of the universe show it is not eternal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Existence of God Part 11 |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/defenders-2-podcast/transcript/s4-11 |website=Defenders Podcast |publisher=Reasonable Faith |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=The End of the World |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/the-end-of-the-world |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231023/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/the-end-of-the-world |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Craig says that postulating a [[multiverse]] of worlds in varying thermodynamic states encounters the problem of [[Boltzmann brains]]—that it becomes highly probable for any observer that the universe is only an illusion of his own brain, a [[solipsism|solipsistic]] conclusion Craig says no [[rational]] person would embrace.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=September 30, 2012 |title=Invasion of the Boltzmann Brains|url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/invasion-of-the-boltzmann-brains |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806180622/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/invasion-of-the-boltzmann-brains |archive-date=August 6, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>

Based on these arguments, Craig concludes that the premise that the universe began to exist is more [[plausibility|plausible]] than not, and conjoined with premise 1, the beginning of the universe implies the existence of a cause. Craig claims that, due to its nature, the cause must be an uncaused, beginningless, changeless, timeless, spaceless, [[matter|immaterial]] being of enormous power, which he refers to as [[God]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Must the Beginning of the Universe Have a Personal Cause? |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/must-the-beginning-of-the-universe-have-a-personal-cause-a-rejoinder |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231439/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/must-the-beginning-of-the-universe-have-a-personal-cause-a-rejoinder |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>

===Divine omniscience===
One of the central questions raised by the classical doctrine of [[omniscience|divine omniscience]] is the compatibility of divine foreknowledge and [[free will]]:
# If God foreknows the occurrence of some event E, does E happen necessarily?{{sfn|Craig|1990}}
# If some event E is contingent, how can God foreknow E's occurrence?{{sfn|Viney|1989}}

According to Craig, the first question raises the issue of [[theological fatalism]]. He attempts to reduce this problem to the problem of logical fatalism, which holds that if it is true that E will happen, then E will happen necessarily. He challenges theological fatalists to show how the addition of God's knowing some future-tense statement to be true adds anything essential to the problem over and above that statement's being true.{{sfn|Zagzebski|2011}}

Craig says that theological fatalists have misunderstood "temporal necessity", or the necessity of the past, and that the impossibility of [[backward causation]] does not imply that one cannot have a sort of [[counterfactual]] power over past events.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=January 7, 2008 |title=Molinism and Free Will |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-and-free-will |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625065855/http://www.reasonablefaith.org:80/molinism-and-free-will |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>

Craig surveyed the rejection of parallel fatalistic arguments in fields other than theology or philosophy of religion.  He reviews discussions of backward causation,{{sfn|Craig|2000b|pp=83–88}}[[time travel]],{{sfn|Craig|2000b|pp=89–96}} the [[special theory of relativity]], [[precognition]],{{sfn|Craig|2000b|pp=97–104}} and [[Newcomb's paradox]] to conclude that fatalistic reasoning has failed.{{sfn|Craig|1987}}

The second question arising from divine foreknowledge of future [[Contingency (philosophy)|contingents]] concerns the means by which God knows such events.<ref>{{cite web |title=Participants: Craig, William Lane |url=http://www.closertotruth.com/participant/William-Lane-Craig/24 |website=Closer to Truth |publisher=Kuhn Foundation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108064505/http://www.closertotruth.com/participant/William-Lane-Craig/24 |archive-date=November 8, 2011 |access-date=October 5, 2011}}</ref>  Craig says that the question presupposes a tensed or [[A-theory of time]], for on a tenseless or [[B-theory of time]] there is no ontological distinction between past, present, and future, so that contingent events which are future relative to us are no more difficult for God to know than contingent events which are, relative to us, past or present.  Distinguishing between perceptualist and [[conceptualist]] models of divine cognition, Craig says that models which construe God's foreknowledge of the future along perceptualist lines (God foresees what will happen) are difficult to reconcile with a tensed theory of time (though one might say that God perceives the present truth-values of future contingent propositions). He does not similarly challenge a conceptualist model which construes God's knowledge along the lines of innate ideas.{{sfn|Craig|2009}}

The doctrine of middle knowledge is one such conceptualist model of divine cognition which Craig has explored.  Formulated by the [[Jesuit]] theologian [[Luis de Molina]], the doctrine of middle knowledge holds that logically prior to his decree to create a world God knew what every possible creature he might create would freely do in any possible set of circumstances in which God might place him.  On the basis of his knowledge of such [[counterfactuals]] of free will<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Does Correspondence Preclude the Truth of Counterfactuals of Freedom?|url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/does-correspondence-preclude-the-truth-of-counterfactuals-of-freedom |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231438/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/does-correspondence-preclude-the-truth-of-counterfactuals-of-freedom |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> and his knowledge of his own decree to create certain creatures in certain circumstances, along with his own decision how he himself shall act, God automatically knows everything that will actually and contingently happen, without any perception of the world.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=September 24, 2007 |title=Middle Knowledge |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/middle-knowledge |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130122852/http://www.reasonablefaith.org:80/middle-knowledge |archive-date=January 30, 2015 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>

Craig has become a proponent of [[Molinism]], supporting middle knowledge and also applying it to a wide range of theological issues, such as [[divine providence]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=April 19, 2010 |title=Molinism vs. Calvinism |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-vs-calvinism |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625031418/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-vs-calvinism |archive-date=June 25, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> and [[predestination]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Molinism and Divine Election |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-and-divine-election |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512214853/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-and-divine-election |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> [[biblical inspiration]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=A Molinist Perspective on Biblical Inspiration |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/a-molinist-perspective-on-biblical-inspiration |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221112/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/a-molinist-perspective-on-biblical-inspiration |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> [[perseverance of the saints]],{{sfn|Craig|1991}} Christian particularism,<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Middle Knowledge and Christian Particularism |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/middle-knowledge-and-christian-particularism |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221926/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/middle-knowledge-and-christian-particularism |archive-date=May 12, 2014 |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> and the [[problem of evil]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=June 7, 2015 |title=Molinism and the Problem of Evil |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/molinism-and-the-problem-of-evil |interviewer-last=Harris |interviewer-first=Kevin |website=Reasonable Faith |type=podcast |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref>

===Divine eternity===
Craig's earlier work on the kalam cosmological argument and on divine omniscience intersected significantly with the philosophy of time and the nature of divine eternity.{{sfn|Craig|Sinclair|2009|pp=184–185}}

Craig examines arguments aimed at showing either that God is timeless or omnitemporal.{{sfn|Craig|2000c}} He defends the coherence of a timeless and personal being, but says that the arguments for divine timelessness are unsound or inconclusive.{{sfn|Craig|1996}} By contrast, he gives two arguments in favor of divine temporality. First, he says that if a temporal world exists, then in virtue of his real relations to that world, God cannot remain untouched by its temporality.{{sfn|Craig|2009}} Craig says that given God's changing relations with the world he must change at least extrinsically, which is sufficient for his existing temporally. Second, Craig says that if a temporal world exists, then in virtue of his omniscience, God must know tensed facts about the world, such as what is happening now, which Craig argues is sufficient for his being temporally located. Craig argues that, since a temporal world does exist, it follows that God exists in time.{{sfn|Craig|1998a}}

Craig says that there is one way of escape from these arguments, which is to accept a B-Theory of time.{{sfn|Craig|2000a}} Craig concludes that one's theory of time is a watershed issue for one's doctrine of divine eternity.{{sfn|Craig|2001c|p=115}}

In ''The Tensed Theory of Time'' (2000) and ''The Tenseless Theory of Time'' (2000), Craig examines the arguments for and against the A- and B-Theories of time respectively.

Elements of Craig's philosophy of time differentiates between time itself and our measures of it (a classical [[Isaac Newton|Newtonian]] theme), and includes an analysis of spatial "tenses" to the location of the "I-now", his defense of [[presentism (philosophy of time)|presentism]], his analysis of McTaggart's paradox{{sfn|Oaklander|2002}} as an instance of the problem of temporary intrinsics, his defense of a neo-Lorentzian interpretation of special relativity, and his formulation of a tensed [[possible worlds]] semantics.{{sfn|Craig|2001c|pp=51–66}}

Craig presents a doctrine of divine eternity and God's relationship to time. Defending [[Leibniz]]'s argument against God's enduring for infinite time prior to creating the universe, and appealing to the kalam cosmological argument, Craig says that God exists timelessly and temporally since the moment of creation.{{sfn|Helm|2011|pp=220ff}} Craig says that [[cosmic time]], which registers the age of the universe, is the measure of God's time. The universe is, Craig concludes, God's clock.{{sfn|Craig|2001a}}

===Resurrection of Jesus===
Craig's two volumes ''The Historical Argument for the Resurrection of Jesus'' (1985) and ''Assessing the New Testament Evidence for the Historicity of the Resurrection of Jesus'' (3rd ed., 2002) are said by the Christian reviewers [[Gary Habermas]] and Christopher Price to be among the most thorough investigations of the event of [[resurrection of Jesus|Jesus' resurrection]].{{sfn|Habermas|1988}}{{verification needed|date=September 2018}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Price |first=Christopher |year=2005 |title=Review of ''The Son Rises: The Historical Evidence for the Resurrection of Jesus'' by William L. Craig |url=http://christiancadre.org/member_contrib/cp_reviews.html#assessing |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103062844/http://christiancadre.org/member_contrib/cp_reviews.html |publisher=Christian Colligation of Apologetics Debate Research & Evangelism |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=September 2018}} In the former volume, Craig describes the [[history]] of the discussion, including [[David Hume]]'s arguments against the identification of [[miracles]]. The latter volume is an [[exegesis|exegetical]] study of the [[New Testament]] material pertinent to the [[resurrection]].

Craig summarizes the relevant evidence under three major heads:{{sfn|Craig|2008|p=360}}

# The [[tomb of Jesus]] was found empty by a group of [[female disciples of Jesus|his female followers]] on the Sunday after his [[crucifixion]].{{sfn|Craig|2001b}}
# Various individuals and groups experienced appearances of Jesus alive after his death. 
#The earliest [[Twelve Apostles|disciples]] came to believe that God had raised [[Jesus]] from the dead despite strong predispositions to the contrary.

Craig's discussion of the evidence for each of these events includes a defense of the traditions of [[entombment|Jesus' burial]] by [[Joseph of Arimathea]], a close exegesis of the Pauline doctrine of the [[resurrection body]], and an investigation of [[pagan]] and [[Judaism|Jewish]] notions of resurrection from the dead.{{sfn|Craig|1985}}

Craig argues that the best explanation of these three events is that God raised Jesus from the dead.<ref>{{cite web |last=Perman |first=Matt |date=September 12, 2007 |title=Historical Evidence for the Resurrection |url=http://www.desiringgod.org/articles/historical-evidence-for-the-resurrection |website=Desiring God |access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> He rejects alternative theories such as [[Gerd Lüdemann]]'s [[hallucination]] hypothesis as lacking explanatory scope, explanatory power, and sufficient historical knowledge to support the psychoanalysis Lüdemann performs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=Visions of Jesus: A Critical Assessment of Gerd Lüdemann's Hallucination Hypothesis |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/visions-of-jesus-a-critical-assessment-of-gerd-ludemanns |website=Reasonable Faith |access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Craig's historical case for the resurrection employs standard historical practices for weighing [[history|historical]] hypotheses concluding that the resurrection is a better match to the available historical data.{{sfn|McGrew|McGrew|2009|p=617}} Specifically, Craig argues, that if one does not begin with the assumption that there is no God, there is a higher probability of the resurrection hypothesis than of its negation, so the resurrection hypothesis is improbable only if one begins with unsupported assumptions.{{sfn|Craig|1986}} Craig also notes that a miraculous explanation of the evidence is increased when one locates the resurrection of Jesus in the context of Jesus' ministry and personal statements.{{sfn|Craig|1998b}} This context, Craig argues, provides the interpretive key to the meaning of Jesus' resurrection as the divine vindication of the allegedly [[blasphemy|blasphemous]] statements for which [[trial of Jesus|Jesus was tried]] and executed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=The Resurrection of Jesus |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/the-resurrection-of-jesus |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001120140/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/the-resurrection-of-jesus |archive-date=October 1, 2017 |access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref>

===Divine aseity===
Craig is currently{{as of when|date=September 2018}} focused on the challenge posed by [[platonism]] to [[divine aseity]] or self-existence.{{sfn|Craig|2014}}{{verification needed|date=September 2018}} Craig rejects the view that God creates [[abstract objects]]{{sfn|Moreland|Craig|2003|pp=506–507}} and defends [[nominalism|nominalistic]] perspectives on abstract objects.{{sfn|Craig|2012a}} Stating that the [[Quine–Putnam indispensability thesis]] is the chief support of platonism,{{sfn|Liggins|2008}} Craig criticizes [[Willard Van Orman Quine]]'s [[naturalized epistemology]] and [[confirmational holism]], and also rejects the metaontological criterion of [[ontological commitment]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=October 28, 2012 |title=Can We Refer to Things That Are Not Present? |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/can-we-refer-to-things-that-are-not-present |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714005601/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/can-we-refer-to-things-that-are-not-present |archive-date=July 14, 2017 |access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref>

Craig favors a neutral logic, according to which the formal quantifiers of [[first-order logic]], as well as the informal quantifiers of ordinary language, are not ontologically committing.{{sfn|Craig|2012b}} He also advocates a deflationary theory of reference, according to which referring is a [[speech act]] rather than a word-world relation, so that singular terms may be used in true sentences without commitment to corresponding objects in the world.{{sfn|Båve|2009}} If one stipulates that first-order [[Quantifiers (logic)|quantifiers]] are being used as devices of ontological commitment, then Craig adverts to [[fictionalism]], in particular pretense theory,{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} according to which statements about abstract objects are expressions of make-believe, imagined to be true, though literally false.{{sfn|Nichols|Stich|1999}}

===Other views===
Craig is a critic of [[metaphysical naturalism]],{{sfn|Craig|Moreland|2000}} [[New Atheism]],{{sfn|Copan|Craig|2009}} and [[prosperity theology]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=March 28, 2010 |title=Lightning Strikes Again |url=https://www.reasonablefaith.org/lightning-strikes-again |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522103904/http://www.reasonablefaith.org:80/lightning-strikes-again |archive-date=May 22, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> as well as a defender of [[Reformed epistemology]].<ref>{{cite web |date=December 30, 2008 |title=Religious Epistemology MP3 Audio by William Lane Craig |url=http://apologetics315.blogspot.com/2008/12/religious-epistemology-mp3-audio-by.html |website=Apologetics 315 |access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> He also states that being a confessing Christian is not compatible with practicing [[homosexuality]].{{sfn|Craig|2003|pp=129–144}}{{page range too broad|date=September 2018}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Zaimov |first=Stoyan |date=April 9, 2013 |title=Christian Apologist Says Church 'Losing Battle' Against Hate Label for Homosexuality Stance |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/christian-apologist-says-church-losing-battle-against-hate-label-for-homosexuality-stance-93566/ |website=The Christian Post |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |title=A Christian Perspective on Homosexuality |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/a-christian-perspective-on-homosexuality |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206173226/http://www.reasonablefaith.org/a-christian-perspective-on-homosexuality |archive-date=December 6, 2016 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=May 19, 2008 |title=Christian Homosexuals? |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/christian-homosexuals |website=Reasonable Faith |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Craig maintains that the theory of [[evolution]] is compatible with Christianity.{{sfn|Stewart|2007}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=February 20, 2012 |title=Evolutionary Theory and Theism |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/evolutionary-theory-and-theism |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002070406/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/evolutionary-theory-and-theism |archive-date=October 2, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Craig has an agnostic position on the creation account.<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |year=2009 |title=William Lane Craig's View on Creation and Evolution |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSc92EDm5gU |website=YouTube |access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Doctrine of Creation |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/defenders-2-podcast/s8 |website=Reasonable Faith |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218203121/https://www.reasonablefaith.org/defenders-2-podcast/s8 |archive-date=December 18, 2015 |access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>{{nonspecific|date=September 2018}} He is a fellow of the [[Discovery Institute]]'s [[Center for Science and Culture]]<ref>{{cite web |title=William Lane Craig |url=http://www.discovery.org/p/85 |publisher=Discovery Institute |access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> and was a fellow of the [[International Society for Complexity, Information, and Design]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Society Fellows |url=http://www.iscid.org/fellows.php |publisher=International Society for Complexity, Information, and Design |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019104148/http://www.iscid.org/fellows.php |archive-date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=October 9, 2011}}</ref>

As a [[divine command theory|divine command theorist]], Craig believes God had the moral right to command the killing of the [[Canaanites]] if they refused to leave their land, as depicted in the [[Book of Deuteronomy]].{{sfnm |1a1=Copan |1a2=Flannagan |1y=2014 |1pp=81–82 |2a1=Howson |2y=2011 |2p=11}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Craig |first=William Lane |date=August 8, 2011 |title=The 'Slaughter' of the Canaanites Re-visited |url=http://www.reasonablefaith.org/the-slaughter-of-the-canaanites-re-visited |website=Reasonable Faith |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> This has led to some controversy. The prominent atheist [[Richard Dawkins]] has repeatedly refused to debate Craig, and has given what he calls Craig's defense of genocide as one of his reasons.<ref name="dawkins2011">{{cite news |last=Dawkins |first=Richard |author-link=Richard Dawkins |date=October 20, 2011 |title=Why I Refuse to Debate with William Lane Craig |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/oct/20/richard-dawkins-william-lane-craig |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="came2011">{{cite news |last=Came |first=Daniel |date=October 22, 2011 |title=Richard Dawkins's Refusal to Debate Is Cynical and Anti-Intellectualist |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2011/oct/22/richard-dawkins-refusal-debate-william-lane-craig |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Richard Dawkins himself came under attack for refusing to debate with William Lane Craig, with fellow atheist Daniel Came saying: {{quote|'The absence of a debate with the foremost apologist for Christian theism is a glaring omission on your CV and is of course apt to be interpreted as cowardice on your part. I notice that, by contrast, you are happy to discuss theological matters with television and radio presenters and other intellectual heavyweights like Pastor Ted Haggard of the National Association of Evangelicals and Pastor Keenan Roberts of the Colorado Hell House.'<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/8511931/Richard-Dawkins-accused-of-cowardice-for-refusing-to-debate-existence-of-God.html</ref>}} He later devoted an article in the Guardian to his refusal, declaring it 'anti-intellectualist' and 'patronising', whilst slating the whole [[New Atheism]] movement for 'replacing one form of irrationality with another.' <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2011/oct/22/richard-dawkins-refusal-debate-william-lane-craig</ref>

Craig has also proposed an [[Apollinarianism|Apollinarian]] Christology in which the divine logos stands in for the human soul of Christ and completes his human nature.{{sfn|Moreland|Craig|2003|p=608}}

==Reception==
According to [[Nathan Schneider]], "[many] professional philosophers know about him only vaguely, but in the field of philosophy of religion, [Craig's] books and articles are among the most cited".<ref name="Schneider 2013"/> [[Sam Harris]] has described Craig as "the one Christian apologist who seems to have put the fear of God into many of my fellow atheists."<ref name="Schneider 2013"/>

Some scholars, such as Wes Morriston of the [[University of Colorado Boulder]], have challenged some of Craig's views, such as the Kalam Cosmological argument,{{sfn|Morriston|2013}} the foundation of God for morality,{{sfn|Morriston|2012}} the alleged genocide of the Canaanites,{{sfn|Morriston|2009}} as well as Craig's views on actual infinites,{{sfn|Morriston|2018}} his fine-tuning argument,{{sfn|Jantzen|2014}} and his arguments for the resurrection of Jesus.{{sfn|Law|2011}}

